{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Two Passes?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The forward-backward algorithm computes the posterior probability γₜ(i) = P(zₜ = sᵢ | x₁:T, λ) — the probability that the system was in hidden state sᵢ at time t, given all observations in the sequence. This quantity is central to the Baum-Welch learning algorithm (the HMM equivalent of the EM M-step)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The key insight is that the posterior at any time t depends on both past and future observations. A single left-to-right pass gives you P(zₜ = sᵢ, x₁:t) — the past is accounted for, but the future is not. A single right-to-left pass gives you P(x_{t+1:T} | zₜ = sᵢ) — the future given the current state, but the past is ignored. Multiplying the two passes gives the full posterior."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Forward-backward algorithm: blue arrows propagate past evidence left-to-right, red arrows propagate future evidence right-to-left; their product gives the posterior"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Forward Pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Define αₜ(i) = P(x₁, …, xₜ, zₜ = sᵢ | λ): the joint probability of seeing x₁:t and being in state i at step t. The recursion is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\alpha_1(i) = \\pi_i \\, B_{i,x_1}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\alpha_t(i) = B_{i,x_t} \\sum_{j=1}^{N} \\alpha_{t-1}(j) \\, A_{ji}, \\quad t > 1"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The marginal likelihood of the full observation sequence is recovered from the final forward variables:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "P(x_{1:T} \\mid \\lambda) = \\sum_{i=1}^{N} \\alpha_T(i)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Backward Pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Define βₜ(i) = P(x_{t+1}, …, xT | zₜ = sᵢ, λ): the probability of seeing the future observations x_{t+1:T}, given that the system is in state i at step t. Boundary condition: βT(i) = 1 for all i (no future observations). The recursion runs backward from T−1 to 1:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\beta_T(i) = 1"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\beta_t(i) = \\sum_{j=1}^{N} A_{ij} \\, B_{j,x_{t+1}} \\, \\beta_{t+1}(j), \\quad t < T"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Combining: State Posteriors"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The state posterior γₜ(i) = P(zₜ = sᵢ | x₁:T) is the normalised product of the forward and backward variables:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\gamma_t(i) = \\frac{\\alpha_t(i) \\, \\beta_t(i)}{\\sum_{j=1}^{N} \\alpha_t(j) \\, \\beta_t(j)}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The denominator is P(x₁:T | λ) and is the same for all states at a given t, so it is just a normalisation constant. For the Baum-Welch M-step we also need the two-time-step posterior ξₜ(i,j) = P(zₜ = sᵢ, z_{t+1} = sⱼ | x₁:T):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\xi_t(i,j) = \\frac{\\alpha_t(i) \\, A_{ij} \\, B_{j,x_{t+1}} \\, \\beta_{t+1}(j)}{\\sum_{i'}\\sum_{j'} \\alpha_t(i') \\, A_{i'j'} \\, B_{j',x_{t+1}} \\, \\beta_{t+1}(j')}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation in Log-Space"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy.special import logsumexp\n\ndef forward_backward(obs_seq, pi, A, B):\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns:\n      gamma : (T, N) state posteriors  γₜ(i)\n      xi    : (T-1, N, N) two-step posteriors ξₜ(i,j)\n      log_likelihood : scalar  log P(x₁:T | λ)\n    \"\"\"\n    T, N = len(obs_seq), len(pi)\n    log_pi = np.log(pi + 1e-300)\n    log_A  = np.log(A  + 1e-300)\n    log_B  = np.log(B  + 1e-300)\n\n    # --- Forward pass ---\n    log_alpha = np.zeros((T, N))\n    log_alpha[0] = log_pi + log_B[:, obs_seq[0]]\n    for t in range(1, T):\n        # log_alpha[t, j] = log B[j, x_t] + logsumexp(log_alpha[t-1] + log_A[:, j])\n        log_alpha[t] = log_B[:, obs_seq[t]] + np.array([\n            logsumexp(log_alpha[t-1] + log_A[:, j]) for j in range(N)\n        ])\n\n    log_likelihood = logsumexp(log_alpha[-1])\n\n    # --- Backward pass ---\n    log_beta = np.zeros((T, N))   # log_beta[T-1] = log(1) = 0\n    for t in range(T-2, -1, -1):\n        # log_beta[t, i] = logsumexp(log_A[i,:] + log_B[:, x_{t+1}] + log_beta[t+1])\n        log_beta[t] = np.array([\n            logsumexp(log_A[i] + log_B[:, obs_seq[t+1]] + log_beta[t+1])\n            for i in range(N)\n        ])\n\n    # --- State posteriors γ ---\n    log_gamma = log_alpha + log_beta\n    log_gamma -= logsumexp(log_gamma, axis=1, keepdims=True)   # normalise\n    gamma = np.exp(log_gamma)   # (T, N)\n\n    # --- Two-step posteriors ξ ---\n    xi = np.zeros((T-1, N, N))\n    for t in range(T-1):\n        log_xi_t = (log_alpha[t, :, None]\n                    + log_A\n                    + log_B[:, obs_seq[t+1]][None, :]\n                    + log_beta[t+1][None, :])\n        log_xi_t -= logsumexp(log_xi_t.ravel())   # normalise\n        xi[t] = np.exp(log_xi_t)\n\n    return gamma, xi, log_likelihood"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Example: State Posteriors on the Weather HMM"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\npi = np.array([0.6, 0.4])\nA  = np.array([[0.7, 0.3], [0.4, 0.6]])\nB  = np.array([[0.6, 0.3, 0.1],   # Sunny: Walk/Shop/Clean\n               [0.1, 0.4, 0.5]])  # Rainy\n\nobservations = [0, 1, 1, 2, 0]   # Walk Shop Shop Clean Walk\n\ngamma, xi, log_lik = forward_backward(observations, pi, A, B)\nstates = [\"Sunny\", \"Rainy\"]\n\nprint(f\"Log-likelihood: {log_lik:.4f}\")\nfor t, obs in enumerate([\"Walk\", \"Shop\", \"Shop\", \"Clean\", \"Walk\"]):\n    print(f\"t={t+1} ({obs}): P(Sunny)={gamma[t,0]:.3f}  P(Rainy)={gamma[t,1]:.3f}\")\n\n# t=1 (Walk):  P(Sunny)=0.874  P(Rainy)=0.126\n# t=2 (Shop):  P(Sunny)=0.572  P(Rainy)=0.428\n# t=3 (Shop):  P(Sunny)=0.446  P(Rainy)=0.554\n# t=4 (Clean): P(Sunny)=0.173  P(Rainy)=0.827\n# t=5 (Walk):  P(Sunny)=0.664  P(Rainy)=0.336\n\n# Note: at t=1 the model is quite confident of Sunny (seeing Walk),\n# but by t=4 after two Shops and a Clean it leans strongly Rainy."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Role in Baum-Welch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Baum-Welch is EM applied to HMMs. The forward-backward pass is the entire E-step: it computes the expected sufficient statistics (γ and ξ) needed to re-estimate all three parameter matrices in the M-step:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Initial distribution:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " π̂ᵢ = γ₁(i) — the posterior at t=1."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Transition matrix:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Âᵢⱼ = Σₜ ξₜ(i,j) / Σₜ γₜ(i) — expected transitions out of i going to j, divided by expected time in i."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Emission matrix:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " B̂ᵢₖ = Σ_{t:xₜ=vₖ} γₜ(i) / Σₜ γₜ(i) — expected time in state i when emitting symbol vₖ, divided by total expected time in i."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each EM iteration is guaranteed to not decrease the log-likelihood P(x₁:T | λ). Convergence is to a local maximum — random restarts help escape poor local optima."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scaling for Numerical Stability"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The log-space implementation above avoids underflow for sequences of several hundred steps. An alternative — the scaled forward-backward — normalises α at each step to sum to 1 and accumulates the log of the scaling factors to recover the log-likelihood. Both approaches are numerically safe; log-space is generally simpler to implement correctly."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
